        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Each solver must demonstrate documented configuration control, a regression test suite covering the element types used, and a traceable release record. Gradation 2 requires documented QMS; Gradation 3 additionally requires independent verification of test suite coverage."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Patch tests, single-element benchmarks, and NAFEMS LE1/LE10 reference problems were executed for all element formulations used (C3D8I hexahedral, CONTA174 contact). Results matched analytical solutions to within 0.5% for linear elastic problems. Nonlinear benchmark (Chaboche cyclic plasticity) matched reference solution within 1.2%. All verification reports archived in the project repository.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Benchmark problems must reproduce analytical or reference solutions within 1% for linear elastic cases and within 2% for nonlinear cases using the element types and material models employed in the production mesh."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted (coarse 42k elements, medium 118k elements, fine 334k elements). Richardson extrapolation yielded a Grid Convergence Index (GCI) of 0.9% for construct stiffness and 1.4% for peak von Mises stress at the screw-rod interface. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, with discretization error contribution to combined uncertainty quantified and propagated into E/uval calculations.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/discretization",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criterion",
        "description": "GCI for primary QoIs must be below 2% on the production mesh. Discretization error must be explicitly included in the combined uncertainty budget."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was monitored via force residual norm (tolerance 1×10⁻⁶) and displacement increment norm (tolerance 1×10⁻⁵) for all load steps. No divergence events were recorded across 33 simulation runs (11 specimens × 3 codes). Time-step sensitivity confirmed that halving the load increment changed QoI predictions by less than 0.3%.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Force and displacement residual norms must reach convergence tolerance at every load step. Load-step sensitivity study must demonstrate QoI change below 1% upon halving the increment."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "A documented modeling protocol specifying mesh generation workflow, boundary condition application, contact pair definitions, and post-processing scripts was followed by all three modeling teams. An independent peer review of input decks was conducted by a fourth analyst not involved in model construction. Discrepancies identified during review (two incorrect contact friction coefficients) were corrected prior to production runs and recorded in the non-conformance log.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criterion",
        "description": "A written modeling protocol must exist and be followed. An independent review of model input decks must be documented, with all identified discrepancies resolved and recorded."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Continuum mechanics with isotropic linear-elastic titanium alloy (E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) and bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (σ_y=880 MPa, E_tan=1.2 GPa) was used. UHMWPE bone surrogate modeled as linear elastic (E=0.9 GPa). Frictional contact (μ=0.2) at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. Model form assumptions were justified against published coupon-level material characterisation data and contact friction measurements from the same lot of hardware. Small-strain assumption validated by confirming maximum principal strain below 2% in the titanium components at 40 mm displacement.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criterion",
        "description": "All constitutive model assumptions must be justified against independent material characterisation data. The validity range of each assumption (e.g. small strain, isotropy) must be confirmed to encompass the simulated loading regime."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Geometry was reconstructed from CMM measurements of each of the 11 physical constructs (dimensional tolerance ±0.01 mm). Material properties were drawn from lot-specific tensile coupon tests (n=5 coupons per lot) rather than literature values. Contact friction coefficients were measured on representative screw-rod pairs using a pin-on-disc tribometer. All input parameter distributions were propagated through Monte Carlo sampling (n=1000 per specimen) to generate the simulation uncertainty u_sim reported in the UQ records.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Geometry inputs must be traceable to dimensional measurements of the tested specimens. Material property inputs must be derived from lot-specific characterisation testing. Uncertainty in all primary inputs must be quantified and propagated to QoI uncertainty."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested, drawn from two independent manufacturing lots and assembled at two independent laboratories. Sample size was justified by a power analysis targeting 80% power to detect a 10% difference in mean stiffness at α=0.05. Dimensional inspection confirmed all specimens within drawing tolerances. Chain of custody documentation links each physical specimen to its corresponding FEA model and experimental data record.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Sample size must be justified by a formal power analysis. Specimens must span at least two manufacturing lots. Dimensional inspection records must be available for all specimens and linked to the corresponding simulation models."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Testing was performed strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single loading rate (10 mm/min) and a single temperature (23 °C). While the protocol is well-controlled and inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed (CV < 3%), only one test condition was evaluated, which does not meet the Gradation 3 requirement for multiple independent test conditions or loading rates. This shortfall is addressed in the offset rationale.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Gradation 3 requires testing under at least two independent conditions (e.g. two loading rates or two temperatures) to confirm model predictive capability across the operating envelope. Gradation 2 requires a single well-characterised condition with documented environmental controls."
      },
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated/factor/test-conditions"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "A formal parameter equivalency table was constructed mapping each experimental measurement (crosshead displacement, applied force, specimen geometry, material lot) to the corresponding FEA input. Traceability was confirmed for all 14 primary input parameters. No surrogate or assumed values were used; all simulation inputs were drawn from measurements taken on the same physical specimens used in testing.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/equivalency",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criterion",
        "description": "A parameter equivalency table must document the mapping between experimental measurements and simulation inputs for all primary parameters. All simulation inputs must be traceable to measurements on the tested specimens, with no unsubstantiated assumed values."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Three scalar QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) were compared using the ASME V&V 10.1 area validation metric and the E/uval criterion. For all three QoIs, E/uval < 1.96 and relative error < 10%. Full force-displacement curve comparison was also performed using the curve-matching metric (Sprague-Geers), yielding magnitude error 1.8% and phase error 0.9%. Results are documented in the three ValidationResult records linked to this package.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criterion",
        "description": "E/uval must be below 1.96 for all primary scalar QoIs. Relative error must be below 10%. Full curve comparison using Sprague-Geers metric must yield magnitude error below 5% and phase error below 5%."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary mechanical performance endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the regulatory submission claims regarding structural adequacy of the pedicle screw construct. A QoI relevance matrix was prepared mapping each QoI to the corresponding clinical failure mode (construct loosening, screw fracture, rod fracture) and regulatory acceptance criterion.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criterion",
        "description": "Each QoI must be traceable to a specific regulatory claim or clinical failure mode via a documented QoI relevance matrix. QoIs must be the same quantities measured in the validation experiments."
      }
